##############################################
DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros(
"PGstandard.pl",
"MathObjects.pl",
"PGML.pl",
"PCCmacros.pl",
"contextInequalities.pl",
"extraAnswerEvaluators.pl"
);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());
$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a =  non_zero_random(-10,10,1);

do {$f = RandomVariableName();} until ($f ne 'x');

Context("Inequalities");
$ans = Interval("(-infinity,-$a)U(-$a,infinity)");

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML
Find the domain of the function [`[$f]`] defined by
    [``[$f](x)=\frac{x+[$a]}{x + [$a]}``]

[__________________________________]{$ans}

[@KeyboardInstructions('You may use interval notation. If the answer is a union of intervals, use [|U|]* for the union symbol. If you need to enter [`\infty`], type [|inf|]*. You may also use an inequality to express the domain, as in [`x\neq1\text{ and }x\neq2`]. To type the [`\neq`] symbol, use [|!=|]*.')@]**
END_PGML

##############################################

$b = -$a;

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

The only potential for an invalid input value would be if the denominator of this expression works out to [`0`]. In this problem, we should not first simplify this function by doing:

    [`` [$f](x) = \frac{x+[$a]}{x + [$a]} = 1 ``]

and say the domain is all real numbers. Instead we should solve [` x+[$a]=0 `] and get [` x=[$b] `], and find the domain to be [`[$ans]`].

END_PGML_SOLUTION


ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
